<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="291" pageId="5" pageNumber="290" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,790]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,331,357]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">Description</emphasis>
(male). Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[582,649,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 9, 10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1992,2016]" captionTargetBox="[230,1352,827,1957]" captionTargetId="figure-209@5.[223,1363,813,1968]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9, 10. Coleolissus, habitus. 9, C. kejvali sp. n. (holotype); 10, C. deformipenis sp. n. (holotype). Scale bar = 1.0 mm." pageId="5" pageNumber="290">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
. Morphological character states are similar to those as described for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Hypolithus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perlucens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">C. perlucens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differing as follows.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,790]" box="[199,796,403,430]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">
Body slightly smaller: length 
<quantity box="[532,620,403,430]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="290" unit="mm" value="8.1">8.1 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[702,791,403,430]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="290" unit="mm" value="3.3">3.3 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,790]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">Head (HWmax/PWmax 0.67, HWmin/PWmax 0.48), with more convex eyes (HWmax/HWmin 1.29). Labrum very shallowly concave anteriorly. Microsculpture on clypeus, frons and vertex highly obliterated, very fine, more or less isodiametric meshes recognized only under and behind eyes.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,790]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">Pronotum (PWmax/PL 1.38, PWmax/PWmin-ap 1.54, PWmax/PWmin-bas 1.29, PWmin-bas/PWmin-ap 1.20), with shallower laterobasal depressions; basal foveae more distinct, very narrow, situated at inner margins of laterobasal depressions.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,790]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">Elytra (EL/EW 1.50, EL/PL 2.54, EW/PWmax 1.22), with subapical sinuation very shallow, but slightly more distinct. Intervals, including lateral ones, impunctate. Interval 3 with a series of 5 (left elytron) and 8 (right elytron) small discal setigerous pores adjoining stria 2 along its entire length. Marginal umbilicate series consisting of 21 (left elytron) and 20 (right elytron) setigerous pores.</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1437,1992,2017]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290" startId="5.[151,264,1992,2016]" targetBox="[230,1352,827,1957]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1992,2017]" box="[151,1437,1992,2017]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,325,1992,2017]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">FIGURES 9, 10.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1892" box="[336,453,1993,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Coleolissus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="290" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[336,453,1993,2017]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">Coleolissus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, habitus. 9, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kataev, 2022" authorityName="Kataev" authorityYear="2022" box="[574,670,1993,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Coleolissus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kejvali" status="sp. n.">
C. 
<emphasis box="[602,670,1993,2017]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">kejvali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[675,731,1993,2017]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[675,731,1993,2017]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(holotype); 10, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kataev, 2022" authorityName="Kataev" authorityYear="2022" box="[891,1052,1993,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Coleolissus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deformipenis" status="sp. n.">
C. 
<emphasis box="[920,1052,1993,2017]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">deformipenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1057,1113,1993,2017]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1057,1113,1993,2017]" pageId="5" pageNumber="290" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(holotype). Scale bar = 1.0 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" box="[199,770,151,177]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Protibia without longitudinal sulcus on dorsal side.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Pro- and metasternum and abdominal sternites almost glabrous, only with a few scattered very fine and short, almost indistinct setae. Apex of last visible sternite (VII) (in male) subtruncate, with one (inner) pair of marginal setae; these setae not distant from margin.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[326,460,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1888,1912]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,892,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-339@6.[151,1436,885,1865]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 11–14. Coleolissus kejvali sp. n., male genitalia (holotype). 11, 12, median lobe of aedeagus; 13, left paramere; 14, right paramere. Left lateral (11, 14), dorsal (12) and right lateral (13) views. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Figs. 11–14</figureCitation>
) slenderer, with relatively smaller basal bulb. Median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[159,241,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1888,1912]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,892,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-339@6.[151,1436,885,1865]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 11–14. Coleolissus kejvali sp. n., male genitalia (holotype). 11, 12, median lobe of aedeagus; 13, left paramere; 14, right paramere. Left lateral (11, 14), dorsal (12) and right lateral (13) views. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) arcuate on dorsal side, with ventral margin rounded in middle portion and slightly convex in the apical quarter, without apical capitulum; in dorsal view median lobe (
<figureCitation box="[869,952,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1888,1912]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,892,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-339@6.[151,1436,885,1865]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 11–14. Coleolissus kejvali sp. n., male genitalia (holotype). 11, 12, median lobe of aedeagus; 13, left paramere; 14, right paramere. Left lateral (11, 14), dorsal (12) and right lateral (13) views. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) more clearly curved to the right apically; terminal lamella rather wide, wider than long, more widely rounded apically. Apical orifice divided into two parts by narrow oblique sclerified bridge: a larger proximal part in dorsal position and a smaller distal one shifted to the left. Internal sac without sclerotic armature.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="291" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,511,537]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after Zbynĕk Kejval (Domažlice, 
<collectingCountry box="[819,1004,511,537]" name="Czech Republic" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Czech Republic</collectingCountry>
), a specialist on Anticidae, one of the collectors of the 
<typeStatus box="[339,387,547,573]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">type</typeStatus>
specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,582,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Comparison.</emphasis>
Very similar in habitus to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1878" box="[656,799,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Hypolithus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perlucens">
<emphasis box="[656,799,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">C. perlucens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from it in having elytral intervals (including lateral ones) impunctate, protibia not sulcate, abdominal sternites not pubescent, apex of last visible abdominal sternite of male subtruncate, with one pair of marginal setae, median lobe of aedeagus with apical orifice divided into two parts by narrow oblique bridge, without apical capitulum and without spines in internal sac, and in other distinctive characters mentioned in the description. The new species differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Ito, 2016" authorityName="Ito" authorityYear="2016" box="[1067,1321,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Coleolissus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nakajimai">
<emphasis box="[1067,1212,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">C. nakajimai</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ito, N." box="[1220,1321,727,753]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291" pagination="359 - 372" refId="ref12220" refString="Ito, N. (2016) Six new species of the Selenophori carabids from India and adjacent regions (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Hatrpalini). Elytra, New Series, 6 (2), 359 - 372." type="journal article" year="2016">Ito, 2016</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
described based on 
<specimenCount box="[255,378,763,789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291" type="female">one female</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[444,576,763,789]" country="India" name="Tamil Nadu" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Tamil Nadu</collectingRegion>
and known to me only from the original description at least in its smaller size (body length 
<quantity box="[301,387,799,825]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.1" pageId="6" pageNumber="291" unit="mm" value="8.1">8.1 mm</quantity>
versus 
<quantity box="[472,576,798,825]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" pageId="6" pageNumber="291" unit="mm" value="12.5">12.5 mm</quantity>
), more convex eyes, non-crenulate elytral striae and fully developed wings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1437,834,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,861]" box="[199,1437,834,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,834,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[604,652,835,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">type</typeStatus>
locality (Kallar river, 
<quantity box="[898,968,835,861]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="291" unit="km" value="30.0">30 km</quantity>
NE of Trivandrum) in 
<collectingRegion box="[1222,1362,835,861]" country="India" name="Kerala" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">Kerala State</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1372,1433,835,861]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="291">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
